          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The femur's shaft is hollow and tubular, while its ends are wide and rough. What</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The femur's shaft is hollow and tubular, while its ends are wide and rough. What is the primary advantage of the shaft being hollow?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It creates space for the growth plate to drive bone elongation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The growth plate is located at the metaphysis, between the shaft and the ends, not within the hollow medullary cavity.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It provides nearly the same strength as solid bone while being significantly lighter</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A hollow tubular design keeps the bone light without sacrificing structural strength — the same engineering principle used in hollow steel pipes.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It allows the nutrient artery to reach the bone's ends without obstruction</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The nutrient artery enters through a small opening in the shaft wall called the nutrient foramen. The hollow cavity is not designed as an arterial conduit.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It provides a flexible zone that absorbs impact during walking</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Bone is rigid by nature, not flexible. Shock absorption occurs at the joints through articular cartilage and synovial fluid, not through the shaft's hollow centre.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The femur's hollow shaft keeps the bone light without sacrificing strength. The wide ends provide surface area for joints and muscle attachments."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The hollow shaft is an engineering solution — strong yet light, much like a hollow pipe."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
