          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient with a femoral shaft fracture reports severe pain. The bone itself has</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with a femoral shaft fracture reports severe pain. The bone itself has very few nerve endings. Which structure is most likely responsible for this pain?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The medullary cavity</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The medullary cavity contains marrow but has minimal nerve endings. It is not the primary source of fracture pain.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The nutrient artery</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The nutrient artery supplies blood to the bone's shaft but does not carry the sensory nerve fibres responsible for pain.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The torn periosteum</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The periosteum is a tough membrane covering the bone's outer surface and is richly supplied with sensory nerves. Fracture pain arises primarily from tearing of this membrane.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The articular cartilage at the bone ends</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Articular cartilage covers joint surfaces at the bone ends, has no nerve supply, and is not located at the fracture site in the shaft.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The bone itself has very few nerve endings. The periosteum — the nerve-rich membrane wrapping the bone's surface — is what makes fractures so painful."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The periosteum carries sensory nerves, and its tearing during fracture is the main source of pain."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
