          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Hilton's Law states that the nerve supplying a muscle also supplies two other st</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Hilton's Law states that the nerve supplying a muscle also supplies two other structures. Which pair is correct?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The bones forming that joint and the adjacent lymph nodes</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hilton's Law relates muscle, joint, and overlying skin — not bones or lymph nodes.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The joint that muscle moves and the skin over its insertion</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hilton's Law (1863) states that the nerve supplying a muscle also supplies the joint that muscle moves and the skin overlying the muscle's insertion. This three-in-one rule is a powerful shortcut for deducing joint innervation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The blood vessels entering that joint and the nearest visceral organ</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Blood vessels and visceral organs are not part of Hilton's Law, which specifically links muscle, joint, and cutaneous innervation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The ligaments of that joint and the contralateral joint of the same type</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The law applies to ipsilateral structures only — the muscle, the joint it acts on, and the overlying skin — not to contralateral joints.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Hilton's Law states that one nerve supplies three related structures: a muscle, the joint that muscle moves, and the skin overlying the muscle's insertion point."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Hilton's Law links three structures to one nerve: the muscle, the joint it moves, and the skin over its insertion."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
